MonitoringLocationDescriptionText: SNAKE RIVER DRAINAGE LONG TERM MONITORING SITE.  SAMPLES WERE TAKEN ANNUALLY FROM 07-13-1988 AND INCREASED TO THREE TIMES A YEAR ON 03-29-1995 AND DECREASED TO SEMI-ANNUALLY IN 2008 BY NDEP PERSONNEL.  NBEH (PRECURSOR TO NDEP) BEGAN SAMPLING AT THIS SITE

IDUSRPC2 is a sub-basin monitoring station located within the Twin Falls Irrigation Tract in the Upper Snake Rock watershed. Water stage in a flume is automatically recorded by a data logger operated by the ARS. The data logger controls a water sampler to collect flow-composite water quality samples from April-October. Air and water temperature are manually recorded weekly when water samples are collected.

IDUSRMC is an irrigation return flow monitoring station on Mud Creek, a tributary of the Snake River that receives seasonal irrigation return flow and continuous flow from subsurface drainage within the Twin Falls Irrigation Tract, which is managed by the Twin Falls Canal Company (TFCC) in the Upper Snake Rock watershed. Water stage at a rated section is automatically recorded by a data logger operated by the Idaho Department of Water Resources (IDWR).  The ARS automatically collects time-composite (5 h interval) water quality samples weekly during the irrigation season, and manually collects water quality samples weekly during the winter. Water and air temperatures and gage height are manually recorded weekly all year.  The actual drainage area may vary due to the area encompassing the irrigation supply and irrigation return flow paths that may not correspond with the DEM.

IDUSRCD is an irrigation return flow monitoring station on Cedar Draw, a tributary of the Snake River that receives seasonal irrigation return flow and continuous flow from subsurface drainage within the Twin Falls Irrigation Tract, which is managed by the Twin Falls Canal Company (TFCC), in the Upper Snake Rock watershed.  Water stage at a rated section is automatically recorded by a data logger operated by the Idaho Department of Water Resources (IDWR).  The ARS automatically collects time-composite (5 h interval) water quality samples weekly during the irrigation season, and manually collects water quality samples weekly during the winter. Water and air temperatures and gage height are manually recorded weekly all year.  The actual drainage area may vary due to the area encompassing the irrigation supply and irrigation return flow paths that may not correspond with the DEM.

IDUSRIC is an irrigation return flow monitoring station on I Coulee located on private property within the Twin Falls Irrigation Tract (TFIT) which is managed by the Twin Falls Canal Company (TFCC), in the Upper Snake Rock watershed. This coulee is a tributary of the Snake River that seasonally contains precipitation runoff and irrigation return flow, and continuous flow from subsurface drainage within the TFCC. Water stage at a 7 ft weir is automatically recorded by a data logger operated by the Idaho Department of Water Resources (IDWR).  Weekly the ARS manually collects a water quality sample, records the gage height, and records the water and air temperature all year.  The actual drainage area may vary due to the area encompassing the irrigation supply and irrigation return flow paths that may not correspond with the DEM.

IDUSRDC is an irrigation return flow monitoring station on Deep Creek, a tributary of the Snake River that receives seasonal irrigation return flow and continuous flow from subsurface drainage within the Twin Falls Irrigation Tract, which is managed by the Twin Falls Canal Company (TFCC) in the Upper Snake Rock watershed. Water stage at a rated section is automatically recorded by a data logger operated by the ARS. The ARS automatically collects time-composite (5 h interval) water quality samples weekly during the irrigation season, and manually collects water quality samples weekly during the winter. Water and air temperatures and gage height are manually recorded weekly all year.  The actual drainage area may vary due to the area encompassing the irrigation supply and irrigation return flow paths that may not correspond with the DEM.

IDUSRRCP is an irrigation return flow monitoring station on Rock Creek, a tributary of the Snake River, at Poleline Road located within the Twin Falls Irrigation Tract, which is managed by the Twin Falls Canal Company (TFCC), in the Upper Snake Rock watershed.  Rock Creek receives flow from IDUSRRCH, seasonal irrigation return flow and continuous subsurface drain flow. Water stage at a rated section is automatically recorded by a data logger operated by the ARS. The ARS automatically collects time-composite (5 h) water quality samples from March-November, and manually collects water quality samples weekly during the winter. Water and air temperature and gage height are manually recorded weekly all year.  The actual drainage area may vary due to the area encompassing the irrigation supply and irrigation return flow paths that may not correspond with the DEM.

IDUSRRCH is a monitoring station on Rock Creek where it crosses under the High Line Canal as it enters the Twin Falls Irrigation Tract, which is managed by the Twin Falls Canal Company (TFCC), in the Upper Snake Rock watershed. Rock Creek flows seasonally from snow melt, precipication and springs originating in the mountains south of the watershed. Water stage measured at a 10 ft weir is automatically recorded by a data logger operated by the ARS. The ARS manually collects water quality samples and records the water and air temperature and gage height weekly when the creek is flowing.  This creek, at this location, does not correspond with a drainage area within the TFIT.

IDUSREC is a sub-basin monitoring station at E Coulee just below the confluence of E2 and F1 and is located within the Twin Falls Irrigation Tract in the Upper Snake Rock watershed. Water stage in a weir (2005) or flume (2006 to present) is automatically recorded by a data logger operated by the ARS.  The data logger controls a water sampler to collect flow-composite water quality samples from April-October. Air and water temperature are manually recorded weekly when water samples are collected.

IDUSRMLA is a monitoring station on the Main Line irrigation canal that delivers water from April through October to the Twin Falls Irrigation Tract, which is managed by the Twin Falls Canal Company (TFCC) in the Upper Snake Rock watershed. Weekly during the irrigation season, the ARS manually collects a water quality sample and records water and air temperature. Water stage is automatically recorded at a rated section near the outlet of Murtaugh Lake, approximately 10 km upstream from this station. This canal also supplies irrigation water to the TF1 sub-basin.  This canal is an irrigation water supply line and does not correspond with a drainage area.

IDUSRA10 is an irrigation return flow monitoring station on A-10 Coulee located on private property within the Twin Falls Irrigation Tract which is managed by the Twin Falls Canal Company (TFCC), in the Upper Snake Rock watershed. This coulee is a tributary of the Snake River that only flows during the irrigation season (April-October). Water stage at a 4 ft weir is automatically recorded by a data logger operated by the Idaho Department of Water Resources (IDWR). Weekly during the irrigation season, the ARS manually collects a water quality sample, records the gage height, and records the water and air temperature.  The actual drainage area may vary due to the area encompassing the irrigation supply and irrigation return flow paths that may not correspond with the DEM.

IDUSRPC1 is a sub-basin monitoring station located within the Twin Falls Irrigation Tract in the Upper Snake Rock watershed. Water stage in a flume is automatically recorded by a data logger operated by the ARS. The data logger controls a water sampler to collect flow-composite water quality samples from April-October. Air and water temperature are manually recorded weekly when water samples are collected.

OrganizationFormalName: National Park Service Water Resources Division

MonitoringLocationDescriptionText: This station is located on the St. Croix River just upstream from the boat landing at Norway Point.  It is located mid-channel, just around the first bend in the river upstream of the boat landing.  The nearest active USGS flow monitoring station is located right at the boat landing for Norway Point (USGS 05336000).
HorizontalCollectionMethodName: GPS Code (Pseudo Range) Standard Position (SA Off)

station_nm: Pool #1 of Lake St. Croix near Bayport, MN
OrganizationFormalName: National Park Service Water Resources Division
MonitoringLocationName: Pool #1 of Lake St. Croix near Bayport, MN
MonitoringLocationDescriptionText: This station is located mid-channel on the St. Croix River in Pool #1 of Lake St. Croix, near Bayport, Minnesota.  The station is East from the tip of the peninsula in Bayport.  The nearest active USGS flow monitoring station is located in St. Croix Falls, Wisconsin (USGS 05340500), which is about 30 miles upstream of the water quality monitoring station.  However, the U.S. Army Corps of Engineers maintains a river stage gage about 2 miles upstream in Stillwater, Minnesota, which indicates river level.  Metropolitan Council Environmental Services (http://www.metrocouncil.org/) is in the process of developing a river discharge rating curve at the Stillwater site by comparing river stage gage measurements with river velocity measurements collected through use of an acoustic Doppler profiler device .
HorizontalCollectionMethodName: GPS Code (Pseudo Range) Standard Position (SA Off)

station_nm: Pool #4 on Lake St. Croix near Prescott, WI

MonitoringLocationName: Pool #4 on Lake St. Croix near Prescott, WI
MonitoringLocationDescriptionText: This station is located mid-channel on the St. Croix River in Pool #4 on Lake St. Croix, about 1.5 miles upstream from where the St. Croix River empties into the Mississippi River.  The nearest active USGS flow monitoring station is located in Prescott, Wisconsin (USGS 05344490), which is about 1 mile downstream of the water quality monitoring station, just before the St. Croix River empties into the Mississippi River.
HorizontalCollectionMethodName: GPS Code (Pseudo Range) Standard Position (SA Off)

A drainage ditch monitoring site on the Miller Ditch near Miller Paul Road in Delaware County, OH.  The site is located in a large agricultural field cropped in corn-soybean rotation and features minimal relief, systematic tile drainage and channelized ditches.  Water samples are collected by automated samplers, as well as weekly grab samples, and analyzed for nutrients and pesticides.

A drainage ditch monitoring site on the Cook Ditch near Green Cook Road in Delaware County, OH.  The site is located in a large agricultural field cropped in corn-soybean rotation and features minimal relief, systematic tile drainage and channelized ditches.  Water samples are collected by automated samplers, as well as weekly grab samples, and analyzed for nutrients and pesticides.

A headwater stream monitoring site located along Sugar Creek at Moody Road in Delaware County, OH.  The site is located in the riparian zone of an unchannelized stream receiving surface runoff.  Water samples are collected by automated samplers, as well as weekly grab samples, and analyzed for nutrients and pesticides.

A headwater stream monitoring site located along Long Run at Peerless Road in Morrow County, OH.  The site is located in the riparian zone of an unchannelized stream receiving surface runoff.  Water samples are collected by automated samplers, as well as weekly grab samples, and analyzed for nutrients and pesticides.

station_nm: St. Croix River About 1 Mile Above Nevers Dam Boat Landing
OrganizationFormalName: National Park Service Water Resources Division
MonitoringLocationName: St. Croix River About 1 Mile Above Nevers Dam Boat Landing
MonitoringLocationDescriptionText: This station is located mid-channel on the St. Croix River about 1 mile upstream from the boat landing at Nevers Dam.  The nearest active USGS flow monitoring station is located in St. Croix Falls, Wisconsin (USGS 05340500), which is about 13 miles downstream of the water quality monitoring station.  The dam is owned by Northern States Power Company.

station_nm: Namekagon River at North Road Just West of Earl, WI
OrganizationFormalName: National Park Service Water Resources Division
MonitoringLocationName: Namekagon River at North Road Just West of Earl, WI
MonitoringLocationDescriptionText: This station is located on the Namekagon River just West of Earl, WI.  Water quality monitoring is conducted from the south side of the bridge over the Namekagon River on North Road.  The nearest active USGS flow monitoring station is located about 9 miles downstream near Trego, Wisconsin at the outlet of the Trego Dam (USGS 05332500).  The dam is owned by Excel Energy.  According to USGS "The data we publish from this site is supplied to us by Excel Energy. We take a few verification measurements but otherwise the data is collected by Excel Energy. We publish the data annually - around March."
